  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nH\n=\n\\int_V\n\\mathbf{A}\\cdot\\mathbf{B}\n\\,\\mathrm{d}^3x .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Quantized Form.}\n\\begin{equation}\nH=w\\,\\Phi .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $\\mathbf{A}$ be the magnetic vector potential and $\\mathbf{B}$ the magnetic field.  \nMagnetic helicity measures the linkage, twist, and winding of magnetic field lines inside a volume $V$:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nH\n=\n\\int_V\n\\mathbf{A}\\cdot\\mathbf{B}\n\\,\\mathrm{d}^3x .\n\\end{equation}\n\nIf the magnetic structure winds around the TZP with integer winding number $w$, and if $\\Phi$ denotes the magnetic flux through the lemniscatic loop, then helicity decomposes into winding times flux:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nH=w\\,\\Phi .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nMagnetic helicity becomes quantized when the field topology is constrained by integer TZP winding.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
